            {% endif %}</div><div data-section-id="pf-560c" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-jWUzzU fYyueS pf-7_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-FNXRL jxoytN"><div class="sc-kfPuZi ihOOoE pf-8_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-dVNjXY jgXfEo pf-9_"><h1 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ctqQKy ldqOxu pf-10_"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-12_">Performance reviews: A manager’s guide</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Performance_reviews_A_manager_s_guide_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695992167" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Performance_reviews_A_manager_s_guide_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695992167 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Performance_reviews_A_manager_s_guide_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_1000x.jpg?v=1695992167 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Performance_reviews_A_manager_s_guide_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1695992167 320w" width="2000" height="1333" alt="Performance reviews: A manager’s guide - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Performance reviews: A manager’s guide - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-ilfuhL fjsXRa pf-13_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-a30f" data-category="Generic Content" data-name="Matcha" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-jWUzzU fYyueS pf-14_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-FNXRL jxoytN"><div class="sc-kfPuZi ihOOoE pf-15_ pf-r pf-c-cb pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px;--s-sm:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-dVNjXY jgXfEo pf-16_"><p class="sc-cbTzjv hvEBKY pf-17_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-19_">In the modern workplace, the performance review process is as anticipated as it is dreaded. It presents a unique challenge for managers: How can you effectively appraise an employee's work, considering their contribution's tangible and intangible aspects?<br><br>Ben Dattner's insightful perspective, as featured in Harvard Business Review, provides a thoughtful blueprint. Building on that, let's delve deeper into delivering a balanced and effective performance review.</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ctqQKy ldqOxu pf-20_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-22_">The power of purposeful goals</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_power_of_purposeful_goals_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695992323" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_power_of_purposeful_goals_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695992323 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_power_of_purposeful_goals_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1695992323 320w" width="2000" height="1360" alt="The power of purposeful goals - Dr Richard Dune -" title="The power of purposeful goals - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-ilfuhL fjsXRa pf-23_"/><p class="sc-cbTzjv hvEBKY pf-24_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-26_">Before you begin, understand why you’re conducting this review. Are you trying to foster growth, point out areas for improvement, or identify future leaders? These goals will shape your review. For instance, if you focus on nurturing talent, you might prioritise feedback encouraging personal development.<br><br><b>Tip</b>: Share your draft with a trusted colleague or mentor. They can help ensure your review aligns with your goals.</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ctqQKy ldqOxu pf-27_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-29_">Behaviour vs. personality: Striking a balance</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Behaviour_vs._personality_Striking_a_balance_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_aded9a24-8da4-4737-9633-3e6c81ff74af.jpg?v=1695995436" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Behaviour_vs._personality_Striking_a_balance_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_aded9a24-8da4-4737-9633-3e6c81ff74af.jpg?v=1695995436 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Behaviour_vs._personality_Striking_a_balance_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_aded9a24-8da4-4737-9633-3e6c81ff74af_500x.jpg?v=1695995436 320w" width="2000" height="1500" alt="Behaviour vs. personality Striking a balance - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Behaviour vs. personality Striking a balance - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-ilfuhL fjsXRa pf-30_"/><p class="sc-cbTzjv hvEBKY pf-31_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-33_">While sticking to the facts is tempting, focusing solely on behaviour or specific incidents might miss the bigger picture. On the other hand, leaning too much into personality could come off as judgmental. The secret is to balance both.<br><br>Consider a situation where an employee consistently misses deadlines. Instead of just stating the fact, delve deeper. Is it a time management issue (behaviour) or an overarching attitude towards work (personality)?<br><br><b>Tip</b>: For every personality-oriented feedback, support it with specific behavioural instances.</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ctqQKy ldqOxu pf-34_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-36_">The delicate dance of authority</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_delicate_dance_of_authority_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695992841" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_delicate_dance_of_authority_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695992841 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_delicate_dance_of_authority_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1695992841 320w" width="2000" height="1334" alt="The delicate dance of authority - Dr Richard Dune -" title="The delicate dance of authority - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-ilfuhL fjsXRa pf-37_"/><p class="sc-cbTzjv hvEBKY pf-38_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-40_">A common pitfall managers often encounter is the desire to be liked. But remember, your role is not about popularity. It's about leadership. While harmonious relationships are essential, it's crucial not to sugarcoat feedback. Your team members look to you for honest, constructive insights to propel their growth.<br><br><b>Tip</b>: Use language that's assertive yet respectful. Statements like, "I've observed..." or "It might be beneficial if..." can be effective.</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ctqQKy ldqOxu pf-41_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-43_">The tone: Your silent communicator</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_tone_Your_silent_communicator_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695992933" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_tone_Your_silent_communicator_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695992933 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/The_tone_Your_silent_communicator_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1695992933 320w" width="2000" height="1245" alt="The tone Your silent communicator - Dr Richard Dune -" title="The tone Your silent communicator - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-ilfuhL fjsXRa pf-44_"/><p class="sc-cbTzjv hvEBKY pf-45_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-47_">The words you use are only half the story. Your tone, both in writing and speech, conveys volumes. Positive feedback delivered in a dismissive tone loses its essence, just as constructive criticism with a harsh tone can seem unduly punitive.<br><br>For instance, saying, "You're always late to meetings", has a different tone than "I've noticed you've been late to a few meetings. Let's discuss how we can improve this."<br><br><b>Tip</b>: Role-playing your review with a colleague can help you calibrate your tone appropriately.</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ctqQKy ldqOxu pf-48_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-50_">Looking ahead: The follow-up</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Looking_ahead_The_follow-up_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695993059" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Looking_ahead_The_follow-up_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695993059 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Looking_ahead_The_follow-up_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1695993059 320w" width="2000" height="1333" alt="Looking ahead The follow-up - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Looking ahead The follow-up - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-ilfuhL fjsXRa pf-51_"/><p class="sc-cbTzjv hvEBKY pf-52_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-54_">A performance review shouldn’t be the end but rather a stepping stone to an employee's future growth. Set clear, realistic, yet challenging goals for the coming period. These objectives should be a blend of performance metrics and learning targets.<br><br><b>Tip</b>: Encourage employees to send a summary email post-review. This ensures mutual understanding and commitment to the agreed-upon goals.</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ctqQKy ldqOxu pf-55_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-57_">Incorporating external models</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Incorporating_external_models_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695993184" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Incorporating_external_models_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695993184 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Incorporating_external_models_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1695993184 320w" width="2000" height="1335" alt="Incorporating external models - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Incorporating external models - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-ilfuhL fjsXRa pf-58_"/><p class="sc-cbTzjv hvEBKY pf-59_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-61_">While Dattner's approach is insightful, integrating other renowned models can further enrich the review process:</span></p><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-jlRLRk gEqlzm pf-62_"><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-dUbtfd iOkFyO pf-63_"><b>The S.M.A.R.T goal framework</b> - When setting post-review objectives, ensure they are Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, and Time-bound. This clarity can drive more effective goal-setting.</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-dUbtfd iOkFyO pf-65_"><b>360-degree feedback</b> - Get a holistic view of an employee’s performance by collecting feedback from peers, subordinates, and superiors. This rounded perspective can offer a more comprehensive review.</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-dUbtfd iOkFyO pf-67_"><b>The sandwich method</b> - Begin with positive feedback, follow with areas for improvement, and conclude with more positive feedback. This method can soften the blow of constructive criticism, making it more digestible.</li><div class="sc-kfPuZi ihOOoE pf-69_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-dVNjXY jgXfEo pf-70_"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-ctqQKy ldqOxu pf-71_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-73_">Conclusion: A continuous journey of improvement</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Conclusion_A_continuous_journey_of_improvement_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695993350" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Conclusion_A_continuous_journey_of_improvement_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1695993350 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Conclusion_A_continuous_journey_of_improvement_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1695993350 320w" width="2000" height="1372" alt="Conclusion A continuous journey of improvement - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Conclusion A continuous journey of improvement - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-ilfuhL fjsXRa pf-74_"/><p class="sc-cbTzjv hvEBKY pf-75_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-dwsnSq jHpHTT pf-77_">Crafting a balanced performance review is both an art and a science. It's about understanding your team members, aligning feedback with overarching goals, and promoting growth.<br><br>As Dattner aptly put it, no one always gets everything right. However, managers can transform the review process from a mere formality into a catalyst for individual and organisational growth with a mindful approach, continuous feedback, and the intent to improve.<br><br>Remember, the journey doesn’t end with one review. It's an ongoing learning process, evolving and striving for excellence - both for the manager and the employee. So, gear up for this rewarding journey and make each review count!</span></p></div></div></div></ul></div></div></div><div class="sc-kfPuZi ihOOoE pf-78_ pf-r pf-r-eh pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide pf-hide" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-dVNjXY jgXfEo pf-79_"><div data-pf-type="Slideshow" class="sc-ksdxgE cobWNe pf-80_"><div data-id="slider-c2da7575-7294-41ed-bc1a-a8dc4771593a-all" class="pf-slider scrollfix"><div class="pf-slide"><div style="display:block" class="sc-hUplSX cGHWkO pf-81_" data-pf-type="SlideshowSlide"><div class="sc-kfPuZi ihOOoE pf-82_ pf-r pf-c-cm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-dVNjXY jgXfEo pf-83_"><div data-pf-type="Image" class="sc-dkYRCH kE